1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,450
Chapter 11 How to Turn Defeat into Victory Social workers and others who work on Skid Row find many differences in age,

2
00:00:12,560 --> 00:00:20,051
religious faith, education, and background among the tragic souls who have dropped into America's gutters.

3
00:00:20,240 --> 00:00:23,171
Some of these citizens are surprisingly young.

4
00:00:23,441 --> 00:00:24,770
Others are old.

5
00:00:24,961 --> 00:00:27,251
A sprinkling are college graduates.

6
00:00:27,360 --> 00:00:30,450
A few have essentially no formal education.

7
00:00:30,641 --> 00:00:31,731
Some are married.

8
00:00:31,841 --> 00:00:32,931
Others are not.

9
00:00:33,281 --> 00:00:36,691
But the people on Skid Row do have something in common.

10
00:00:36,881 --> 00:00:40,450
Each one is defeated, whipped, beaten.

11
00:00:40,721 --> 00:00:44,291
Each one has encountered situations that conquered him.

12
00:00:44,561 --> 00:00:52,051
Each is eager, even anxious, to tell you about the situation that wrecked him, about his own private Waterloo.

13
00:00:53,281 --> 00:00:59,490
These situations cover the waterfront of human experience, from my wife ran out on me,

14
00:00:59,681 --> 00:01:03,651
to I lost everything I had and had no place else to go,

15
00:01:03,841 --> 00:01:07,651
to I did a couple of things that made me a social outcast,

16
00:01:07,761 --> 00:01:09,651
so I came down here.

17
00:01:10,641 --> 00:01:16,131
When we move up from Skid Row into the dominion of Mr. and Mrs. Average American,

18
00:01:16,321 --> 00:01:19,170
we see obvious differences in living habits.

19
00:01:19,361 --> 00:01:31,011
But again, we discover that Mr. Mediocre gives essentially the same reasons to explain his mediocrity as Mr. Skid Row gave to explain his complete collapse.

20
00:01:31,441 --> 00:01:34,931
Inside, Mr. Mediocre feels defeated.

21
00:01:35,121 --> 00:01:39,411
He has unhealed wounds suffered in situations that beat him.

22
00:01:39,681 --> 00:01:41,731
Now he is supercautious.

23
00:01:41,920 --> 00:01:47,810
He plods along, ducking the thrill of living victoriously, discontented with himself.

24
00:01:48,161 --> 00:01:55,250
He feels beaten, but tries hard to endure the sentence of mediocrity that fate has handed him.

25
00:01:55,920 --> 00:02:02,851
He too has surrendered to defeat, but in a reasonably clean, socially accepted way.

26
00:02:03,921 --> 00:02:12,451
Now, when we climb upstairs into the uncrowded world of success, we again discover people from every possible background.

27
00:02:12,720 --> 00:02:21,011
Corporate executives, leading ministers, government officials, top men in every field, we discover come from poor homes,

28
00:02:21,040 --> 00:02:26,211
rich homes, broken homes, cotton patches, cornfields, and slums.

29
00:02:26,560 --> 00:02:33,891
These people, who lead every branch of our society, have experienced every tough situation you can describe.

30
00:02:34,560 --> 00:02:42,611
It is possible to match every Mr. Skid Row with a Mr. Mediocre and a Mr. Success on every score,

31
00:02:42,880 --> 00:02:48,690
age, intelligence, background, nationality, you name it, with one exception.

32
00:02:48,961 --> 00:02:53,410
The one thing you can't match them on is their response to defeat.

33
00:02:54,080 --> 00:02:59,250
When the fellow we call Mr. Skid Row got knocked down, he failed to get up again.

34
00:02:59,440 --> 00:03:02,211
He just lay there, splattered out.

35
00:03:02,480 --> 00:03:08,051
Mr. Mediocre got up to his knees, but he crawled away, and when out of sight,

36
00:03:08,320 --> 00:03:13,810
ran in the opposite direction, so he'd be sure never to take a beating again.

37
00:03:14,560 --> 00:03:18,771
But Mr. Success reacted differently when he got knocked down.

38
00:03:18,961 --> 00:03:23,651
He bounced up, learned a lesson, forgot the beating, and moved upward.

39
00:03:24,320 --> 00:03:29,571
One of my closest friends is an exceptionally successful management consultant.

40
00:03:29,920 --> 00:03:34,530
When you walk into his office, you feel that you are really uptown.

41
00:03:34,640 --> 00:03:42,371
The fine furniture, the carpeting, the busy people, the important clients, all tell you his company is prosperous.

42
00:03:43,200 --> 00:03:49,410
A cynic might say, it must have taken a real con man to put across an operation like this.

43
00:03:49,600 --> 00:03:51,331
But the cynic would be wrong.

44
00:03:51,440 --> 00:03:53,331
It didn't take a con man.
